On Mon, Jan 2, 2012 at 12:33 PM, Mark Derricutt &lt;mark@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; My intention would be to tell the customer that he&#39;s been sent a &quot;customer&quot;, in JSON format.

[snip]

&gt; I&#39;d see this is a vague intermediary step - just as a client makes assumptions based on a spec on what following a link rel of &quot;edit&quot; may return, so two could the assumptions of parsing a &quot;customer&quot; object.
&gt;
&gt; If need be - the header could specialized further with:
&gt;
&gt; Content-Disposition: inline; concept=customer; version=1.2; schema=http://.....customer12.xsd

It looks suspiciously like you&#39;re trying to solve the same problem as:

   - The &quot;profile&quot; content-type parameter in JSON schema:

       https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-zyp-json-schema-03

       http://json-schema.org/

   - The &quot;profile&quot; link relationship (seemingly not IANA registered):

       http://microformats.org/wiki/profile-uris

       http://microformats.org/wiki/rel-profile

       http://microformats.org/wiki/existing-rel-values

Media type specialisation (via a &quot;profile&quot; parameter) allows
server-side content negotiation based on Accept.

I guess the &quot;profile&quot; and &quot;alternate&quot; link relationships require
clients to download multiple versions to perform client-side content
selection. But if the goal is less content negotiation than defining
which vocabulary is actually in use, the profile relationship works
fine and can provided out-of-band via the Link HTTP header.

